					Full Description



HCSB Financial Corporation, incorporated on March 15, 1999, is a holding company for Horry County State Bank (the Bank). The Bank is a state chartered bank. Its primary market includes Horry County in South Carolina and Columbus and Brunswick Counties in North Carolina. The Company's segments include Commercial, Commercial Real Estate, Consumer and Residential. From its over eight branch locations, it offers a range of deposit services, including checking accounts, savings accounts, certificates of deposit, money market accounts, and individual retirement account (IRAs), as well as a range of non-deposit investment services. In addition, it offers a range of loan products designed for consumers, businesses and farmers. Its net loans total over $204.8 million and deposits total over $330.8 million.The Bank also offers other services, such as cash management services, sweep accounts, repurchase agreements, mobile banking, remote deposit capture, safe deposit boxes, travelers checks, direct deposit of payroll and social security checks, online banking and automatic drafts for various accounts. It is associated with a shared network of automated teller machines that can be used by its customers throughout South Carolina and other regions. One of its non-executive officers is a registered representative of Investment Professionals Inc. (IPI), and through this individual, it offers investments in securities and other non-deposit investment products. It also offers MasterCard and VISA credit card services through a third-party vendor.Lending ActivitiesThe Company provides a range of lending activities, including real estate, commercial, agricultural and consumer loans, to individuals and small to medium-sized businesses and professional concerns that are located in or conduct a substantial portion of their business in its market area. The primary component of its loan portfolio is loans collateralized by real estate, which make up approximately 84.2% of its loan portfolio. Residential real estate loans are 35.9% of the portfolio. These loans are secured generally by first or second mortgages on residential, agricultural or commercial property and consists of commercial real estate loans and residential real estate loans (but exclude home equity loans, which are classified as consumer loans). Its commercial real estate loans total over $101.3 million. Commercial loans consist of secured and unsecured loans, lines of credit, and working capital loans. It makes these loans to various types of businesses. Included in this category are loans to purchase equipment, finance accounts receivable or inventory, and loans made for working capital purposes.Consumer loans make up approximately 2.5% of its loan portfolio. These are loans made to individuals for personal and household purposes, such as secured and unsecured installment and term loans, home equity loans and lines of credit, and revolving lines of credit, such as overdraft protection. Automobiles, recreational boats and small recreational vehicles are often pledged as collateral on secured consumer loans. Approximately 3.2% of its loan portfolio consists of agricultural loans. These are loans made to individuals and businesses for agricultural purposes, including loans to finance crop production and livestock operating expenses, to purchase farm equipment, and to store crops. These loans are secured generally by liens on growing crops and farm equipment. Also included in this category are loans to agri-businesses, which are substantially similar to commercial loans.Investment ActivitiesThe Company's investment securities are classified as available-for-sale. The Company's securities portfolio consists of mortgage securities, government agency bonds and municipal bonds. The Company's portfolio of available-for-sale securities total over $89.7 million.Sources of FundsThe primary sources of funds of the Bank are customer deposits and loan repayments. It offers a range of deposit services, including negotiable order of withdrawal (NOW) accounts and time deposits of various types, ranging from daily money market accounts to longer-term certificates of deposit.

